          {
            "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/13326805/comment/17240906",
            "id": "17240906",
            "author": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=epayne",
              "name": "epayne",
              "key": "eepayne",
              "avatarUrls": {
                "48x48": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?ownerId=eepayne&avatarId=40831",
                "24x24": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&ownerId=eepayne&avatarId=40831",
                "16x16": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&ownerId=eepayne&avatarId=40831",
                "32x32": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&ownerId=eepayne&avatarId=40831"
              },
              "displayName": "Eric Payne",
              "active": true,
              "timeZone": "Etc/UTC"
            },
            "body": "[~wjlei], thank you for your reply.\r\nbq. this design is a inner yarn level to organize different jobs. And it can unit different platform submitting jobs to yarn.\r\nCan you please be more specific about uniting different platforms submitting jobs to yarn? I see the following from the above design document:\r\n\"one batch job may trigger several sub-jobs to running at the same time, like one job to process the data and another one monitor job metrics. And when we want to cancel these jobs, we must kill them one by one in current design. I proposal a job group concept to handle such parent-child jobs as one unit.\"\r\n\r\nI believe that Oozie (oozie.apache.org) can provide this type of support. It can launch many different types of jobs such as pig, tez, hive, spark, python, shell actions, and probably many others. Oozie is a well-established coordinator that launches regularly recurring jobs. Oozie can group jobs together with upstream and downstream dependencies in a directed graph. Oozie has a community of support in Apache.\r\n\r\nIf I have misunderstood your requirements, please help me to understand how Oozie does not meet them.\r\n\r\nI suggest that you take a look at the Oozie documentation and reach out to the users@oozie.apache.org or dev@oozie.apache.org mailing lists.",
            "updateAuthor": {
              "self": "https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=epayne",
              "name": "epayne",
              "key": "eepayne",
              "avatarUrls": {
